olitical performance that ranged from marches and sit-ins to jail-ins and speeches, these artists turned to theater to unsettle a violent racial project that Fleming refers to as “Black patience.” Inviting the likes of James Baldwin, Lorraine Hansberry, Alice Childress, Douglas Turner Ward, Duke Ellington, and Oscar Brown Jr. to the stage, Black Patience illuminates how Black artists and activists of the Civil Rights era used theater to expose, critique, and repurpose structures of white supremacy. In this bold rethinking of the Civil Rights Movement, Fleming contends that Black theatrical performance was a vital technology of civil rights activism, and a crucial site of Black artistic and cultural production.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican American theaterxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aTheater and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aTimexPhilosophyxHistoryy20th century. 7aART / Performance.2bisacsh  aAffect.  aAmiri Baraka.  aBlack Ontology.  aCivil Rights Movement.  aDisappearance.  aDouglas Turner Ward.  aDuke Ellington.  aEmancipation.  aFree Southern Theater.  aFreedom.  aJail-ins.  aJames Baldwin.  aLorraine Hansberry.  aMississippi.  aMovement.  aPaul Carter Harrison.  aPerformance.  aPlantation Geographies.  aQueer Futures.  aQueer Time.  aRace.  aRadicalism.  aSit-ins.  aSlavery.  aStillness.  aThe Erotic.  aTheatre.  aTime.  aTransnationalism.  aU.S. South.  aVisual Culture.  aWhiteness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2022z9783110992809oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2022 Englishz978311099281608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PA